import pandas as pd

# Loading the uploaded CSVs
df = pd.read_csv("unicefindicator2.csv")
meta = pd.read_csv("unicefmetadata.csv")

# Previewing first few rows
df.head()
Code 
print("Main dataset columns:")
print(df.columns)

print("\nMetadata columns:")
print(meta.columns)
Code 
# Filtered to only include "Total" gender
df_total = df[df["sex"] == "Total"].copy()
Code 
# Renamed columns for clarity
df_total = df_total.rename(columns={
    "obs_value": "inactivity_pct",
    "time_period": "year"
})
Code 
# Ensuring year is numeric
df_total["year"] = df_total["year"].astype(int)
Code 
# Checking for missing data
df_total.isnull().sum()
Code 
df_total.head()
Code 
# Group and calculate yearly average
df_time = df_total.groupby("year", as_index=False)["inactivity_pct"].mean()

# Preview
df_time.head()

1.1 Global Trend in Adolescent Physical Inactivity (2001â€“2016)

This chart shows that adolescent physical inactivity remained consistently high between 2001 and 2016, with minimal signs of improvement.
Despite growing awareness of health risks, a large share of 11â€“17-year-olds globally remain insufficiently active.

Below is the chart visualizing this global trend:

Code 
from plotnine import *

# Build the time-series chart
time_series_plot = (
    ggplot(df_time, aes(x="year", y="inactivity_pct")) +
    geom_line(color="#0072B2", size=1.5) +
    geom_point(color="#D55E00", size=2) +
    scale_y_continuous(limits=[60, 90], breaks=range(60, 91, 5)) +
    labs(
        title="Global Trend in Adolescent Physical Inactivity (2001â€“2016)",
        subtitle="Data for adolescents aged 11â€“17 from 146 countries",
        x="Year",
        y="Inactivity (%)",
        caption="Source: UNICEF Dataset"
    ) +
    theme_light() +
    theme(
        plot_title=element_text(size=14, weight="bold"),
        plot_subtitle=element_text(size=11, color="gray"),
        axis_text=element_text(size=10),
        axis_title=element_text(size=12),
        figure_size=(10, 5)
    )
)

# Show plot
time_series_plot
Code 
time_series_plot.save("inactivity_trend.png", dpi=300)

1.2 Adolescent Physical Inactivity by Country (2015)

This world map shows the percentage of adolescents aged 11â€“17 in each country who were insufficiently physically active in 2015.
Higher inactivity rates appear in parts of the Middle East, Latin America, and Southeast Asia, pointing to regional disparities in youth physical activity.

Code 
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Creating the plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(15, 10))

map_2015.plot(
    column="inactivity_pct",
    ax=ax,
    cmap="YlOrRd",  # Red-yellow color
    legend=True,
    edgecolor="black",
    missing_kwds={
        "color": "lightgrey",
        "label": "No data"
    }
)

# Add title and remove axis
plt.title("Adolescent Physical Inactivity by Country (2015)", fontsize=15)
plt.axis('off')

# Show the map
plt.show()

1.3 Top 10 Countries by Adolescent Inactivity

This chart displays the ten countries with the highest average levels of adolescent physical inactivity between 2001 and 2016.
Many of the top-ranking countries are from Southeast Asia and the Middle East, where cultural and environmental factors may limit physical activity opportunities for youth.

Code 
from plotnine import *

# Building the bar chart
bar_chart = (
    ggplot(top10, aes(x="reorder(country, inactivity_pct)", y="inactivity_pct")) +
    geom_bar(stat="identity", fill="#E69F00") +
    coord_flip() +
    labs(
        title="Top 10 Countries by Adolescent Inactivity (2001â€“2016)",
        subtitle="Average % of insufficiently active adolescents aged 11â€“17",
        x="Country",
        y="Average Inactivity (%)"
    ) +
    theme_light() +
    theme(
        plot_title=element_text(size=14, weight="bold"),
        plot_subtitle=element_text(size=11, color="gray"),
        axis_text=element_text(size=10),
        axis_title=element_text(size=12),
        figure_size=(10, 6)
    )
)

Code 
meta_clean = meta.rename(columns={
    "GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)": "gdp_per_capita",
    "year": "year"
})

# Get latest year per country
latest_meta = meta_clean.sort_values("year").drop_duplicates("country", keep="last")

# Keeping only country and GDP columns
latest_meta = latest_meta[["country", "gdp_per_capita"]]

# Preview
latest_meta.head()
Code 
# Merging inactivity and GDP
scatter_df = pd.merge(avg_inactivity, latest_meta, on="country", how="left")

# Drop missing GDP values
scatter_df = scatter_df.dropna(subset=["gdp_per_capita"])

# Preview
scatter_df.head()

1.4 GDP vs Adolescent Physical Inactivity

This scatterplot examines the relationship between a countryâ€™s economic prosperity (GDP per capita) and the average adolescent inactivity rate.
The negative trendline suggests that adolescents in wealthier countries are generally more active, potentially reflecting better access to sports facilities, health education, and recreation spaces.

Code 
from plotnine import *

# Creating scatterplot
scatter_plot = (
    ggplot(scatter_df, aes(x="gdp_per_capita", y="avg_inactivity")) +
    geom_point(color="#56B4E9", size=2) +
    geom_smooth(method="lm", se=False, color="black") +
    labs(
        title="GDP vs Adolescent Physical Inactivity",
        subtitle="Countries with higher GDP tend to show lower inactivity",
        x="GDP per Capita (USD)",
        y="Average Inactivity (%)"
    ) +
    theme_light() +
    theme(
        plot_title=element_text(size=14, weight="bold"),
        plot_subtitle=element_text(size=11, color="gray"),
        axis_text=element_text(size=10),
        axis_title=element_text(size=12),
        figure_size=(10, 6)
    )
)

# Show plot

Code 
# Filtering to Male and Female rows
df_gender = df[df["sex"].isin(["Male", "Female"])].copy()

# Preview
df_gender.head()
Code 
gender_pivot = df_gender.pivot_table(
    values="obs_value",
    index=["country", "time_period"],
    columns="sex"
).reset_index()

# Preview
gender_pivot.head()
Code 
gender_pivot["gender_gap"] = gender_pivot["Female"] - gender_pivot["Male"]

# Preview
gender_pivot.head()
Code 
gap_avg = gender_pivot.groupby("country")["gender_gap"].mean().reset_index()
gap_avg = gap_avg.sort_values("gender_gap", ascending=False)

# Preview
gap_avg.head()

1.5 Gender Gap in Adolescent Physical Inactivity

This chart shows the difference in average inactivity levels between adolescent girls and boys.
In most countries, the gap is positive, indicating that girls are more likely to be insufficiently active.
This could reflect barriers like safety, cultural norms, or fewer opportunities for structured physical activity.

Code 
# Keeping only Top 20 countries
gap_avg_top20 = gap_avg.head(20)

# Plotting the chart
gender_plot = (
    ggplot(gap_avg_top20, aes(x="reorder(country, gender_gap)", y="gender_gap")) +
    geom_bar(stat="identity", fill="#CC79A7") +
    coord_flip() +
    labs(
        title="Top 20 Countries: Gender Gap in Adolescent Inactivity",
        subtitle="Positive values = females more inactive",
        x="Country",
        y="Female âˆ’ Male Inactivity (%)"
    ) +
    theme_light() +
    theme(
        plot_title=element_text(size=16, weight="bold"),
        plot_subtitle=element_text(size=12, color="gray"),
        axis_text=element_text(size=10),
        axis_title=element_text(size=12),
        figure_size=(12, 10)
    )
)

# Show chart
gender_plot

1.6 Conclusion

Multi-stakeholder interventions are needed to tackle adolescent inactivity globally.
Programs must consider regional, economic, and gender differences to be effective.
